<DOC><DOCNO> AP880223-0279 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0647EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   02-23 0451</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0473</SECOND><DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge has blocked asunconstitutional an Ohio takeover statute aimed at thwartingCampeau Corp.'s attempted hostile takeover of Federated DepartmentStores Inc.   Toronto-based Campeau has a hostile $5.4 billion offer pendingfor Cincinnati-based Federated. Campeau is offering $5.8 billion ifFederated agrees to a friendly merger.   State officials have not decided whether to appeal Monday'sruling, a spokesman said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The federal government posted a rare $16.09billion surplus last month, primarily because Social Securitychecks for January were mailed early, the Treasury Department says.   The early payment inflated government spending in December andlowered spending in January, the department said Monday. TheDecember deficit was $24.22 billion.   For all of 1988, the Reagan administration is projecting thebudget deficit will fall to $146.74 billion, down 2.5 percent fromlast year's deficit of $150.4 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Reagan administration has confirmed it isinvestigating allegations that a U.S. computer system which couldhelp determine optimal targets for nuclear missiles had beenillegally shipped to the Soviet Union.   According to a report in Monday editions of the WashingtonTimes, Essex Marketing Co. of Los Angeles is under investigationfor an alleged shipment Dec. 21 of the computer to an engineeringcollege in Zagreb, Yugoslovia.   The computer was diverted and wound up in the Soviet Unioninstead, the newspaper said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has upheld a ruling thatsharply curtails the power of communities to regulate cabletelevision.   The high court turned away an appeal by Palo Alto and Atherton,Calif., which wanted to enforce public access and other ruleschallenged by cable operator Century Federal Inc.   But the court's action apparently was based on narrow proceduralgrounds and leaves open the possibility of a subsequent appeal.</TEXT><DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A survey of 226 large and medium-sizedAmerican companies found 70 percent have restricted or are preparedto limit smoking in the workplace.   ``I was really surprised at the extent to which this hadsurfaced as a personnel issue,'' Victor Lindquist, author of theNorthwestern University Lindquist-Endicott Report, said Monday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market gained broadly Monday, extending its recentrally in a mood of increasing optimism about the economic outlook.The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.70 to 2,040.29.   Bond prices finished modestly higher. The yield on theTreasury's closely watched 30-year issue, which moves inversely toits price, slipped to 8.41 percent from 8.43 percent late Friday.   The dollar drifted lower. Gold prices were narrowly mixed.   Cotton futures prices collapsed; grains and soybeans were mostlylower; and livestock and meat were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>